[[File:Heiankyo palace location.png|250px|thumb|Heian-kyō. '''Suzaku Avenue''' shown in bold vertical line]]

{{Nihongo|'''Suzaku Avenue''' or '''Suzaku Boulevard'''|朱雀大路|Suzaku Ōji}} is the name given to the central avenue leading to the Imperial Palace from the south in [[Japan]]ese capitals. As per tradition, the Imperial palace complex typically faces south, whilst Suzaku Avenue leads directly away from the main gate. Cities were often based on the traditional, Chinese grid-pattern style, which means Suzaku Avenue was typically the central road within the city grid and, as a result, the widest. [[Fujiwara-kyō]], [[Heijō-kyō]], [[Heian-kyō]] had their own Suzaku Avenue.

==Route==
In [[Heian-kyō]], present [[Kyoto]], the [[Rashōmon]] (Rajōmon, Raseimon) was at the southern end of Suzaku Avenue, whilst at the northern end there was the main gate of [[Heian Palace]]. Here though, Suzaku Avenue stopped being the central street, due to gradual abandonment of the west of the city. Eventually, the road served as the western boundary of the town, until the [[Meiji period]]. Presently it is still a major street called {{Nihongo|Senbon Street or Senbon Avenue|千本通|Senbon Dōri}} and once served as a route for the city's [[tram]]line.

The word "[[Suzaku]]", refers to the Guardian God of the South, who was said to appear in the form of a bird.

