[[sn:Suzaku Avenue]] [[en:Suzaku Avenue]]
[[Category:Pages without translation templates]] [[Category:pages with valid en interwikis]] <!--enwiki derived wikidata interwikis--> {{Commons category|Suzaku Avenues}} [[fr:Avenue Suzaku]] [[id:Adimarga Suzaku]] [[ja:朱雀大路]] [[zh:朱雀大路]]

{{Unreferenced|auto=yes|date=December 2009}}
[[File:Heiankyo palace location.png|250px|thumb|Heian-kyō. '''Suzaku Avenue''' shown in bold vertical line]] [[File:SuzakuOji street of Heiankyo.jpg|thumb|220px|A reconstructed model of Suzaku Avenue and Rashōmon exhibited at Heiankyo Sosei-Kan Museum]] {{Nihongo|'''Suzaku Avenue''' or '''Suzaku Boulevard'''|朱雀大路|Suzaku Ōji}} is the name given to the central avenue leading to the Imperial Palace from the south in [[Japan]]ese capitals. Traditionally the Imperial palace complex faces south, whilst Suzaku Avenue leads directly away from the main gate. Cities were often based on a traditional Chinese grid pattern. Suzaku Avenue was typically the central road within the city grid, and as a result, the widest. [[:en:Fujiwara-kyō|Fujiwara-kyō]], [[Heijō-kyō]], and [[Heian-kyō]] had their own Suzaku Avenue.
The word "[[Vermilion Bird|Suzaku]]" refers to the Guardian God of the South, who was said to appear in the form of a bird.
==Heian-kyō== In Heian-kyō, present-day [[Kyoto]], the [[Rajōmon]] (Rajōmon, Raseimon) was at the southern end of Suzaku Avenue, flanked on the east by the temple of [[Tō-ji]], and on the west by the temple of [[Sai-ji]], whilst at the northern end there was the main gate [[Suzakumon]] of [[Heian Palace]]. Of these, only Tō-ji remains.
Over time Suzaku Avenue stopped being the central street, due to the gradual abandonment of the west of the city. Eventually the road served as the western boundary of the town, until the [[Meiji period]]. Presently it is still a major street, called {{Nihongo|Senbon Street or Senbon Avenue|千本通|Senbon Dōri}}, and once served as a route for the city's [[tram]]line.
==Fujiwara-kyō==
==Heijō-kyō==
